  <section id="section-1">
    <h2>1. How local lead generation differs from general lead generation</h2>
    <p>Understanding what makes local lead generation distinct is the first step to allocating effort correctly. Three differences define the local context.</p>
    <h3>Geography constrains and concentrates the audience</h3>
    <p>A national or online business can acquire customers from anywhere and scale lead volume by reaching a broader audience. A local business cannot. This means every lead generation method must either target your geographic area specifically or leverage the proximity signals (distance, directions, "near me") that govern local search and discovery. Methods that work at national scale — mass email campaigns, viral content marketing — produce poor returns for local businesses because most of the audience reached is outside the service area.</p>
    <h3>Proximity intent drives the highest-quality traffic</h3>
    <p>When someone searches "emergency plumber near me" or "best physio in [suburb]," they are ready to act — the intent is immediate and the commitment to purchase is high. This is fundamentally different from someone browsing a general article about plumbing or physiotherapy. Local lead generation methods that capture proximity intent (Google Business Profile, local SEO, Google Local Service Ads) produce leads with the shortest sales cycles and highest close rates of any channel available to a local business.</p>
    <h3>Reputation compounds faster — and falls harder</h3>
    <p>In a local market, every customer interaction affects your lead generation. A bad review from one dissatisfied customer is visible to everyone in your service area. A strong word-of-mouth reputation drives inbound leads that cost nothing to acquire and convert at rates no paid channel can match. Local lead generation and local reputation management are the same activity — every satisfied customer is a potential lead source; every dissatisfied one is a potential lead blocker.</p>
    <Callout type="info">
      <strong>The local lead generation priority order:</strong> Fix your Google Business Profile and review count first. These two things determine whether people can find you and whether they trust what they find. Traffic from any other channel — ads, social, referrals — flows to your GBP listing and your reviews before it reaches you. Build the foundation before the channels.
    </Callout>
  </section>
  <section id="section-2">
    <h2>2. Google Business Profile optimisation</h2>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-header">
        <span class="mc-num">01</span>
        <span class="mc-title">Google Business Profile (GBP)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mc-body">
        <div class="mc-stats">
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Cost</span><span class="val">Free</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Setup Time</span><span class="val">2–4 hours</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">First Leads</span><span class="val">Days–Weeks</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Compounds</span><span class="val">Yes — over months</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Google Business Profile is the free listing that appears in Google Maps and in the "local pack" — the group of three local businesses that appears above organic search results for location-specific queries. It is the single highest-ROI lead generation action available to most local businesses, because it targets people who are already searching for exactly what you offer, in your area, right now.</p>
        <p><strong>What a fully optimised GBP does:</strong> It shows up in local pack results for relevant searches, displays your phone number and directions prominently, shows your hours, photos, and recent reviews, and allows customers to book appointments or send messages directly from the search result. For many service businesses, the majority of inbound leads now originate from the GBP listing rather than the website.</p>
        <p><strong>The most impactful optimisation actions:</strong></p>
        <ul class="action-list">
          <li>Complete every field — business name, address, phone (consistent with your website), category, service area, hours, and description</li>
          <li>Add high-quality photos of your premises, work, team, and products — businesses with 100+ photos receive significantly more views</li>
          <li>Post weekly updates (Google Posts) — offers, events, new services — each post increases visibility for 7 days</li>
          <li>Respond to every review, positive and negative — response rate is a visible trust signal</li>
          <li>Add your services or products with descriptions and prices where applicable</li>
          <li>Enable messaging and respond within hours — Google rewards fast response rates with higher placement</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Common errors that suppress rankings:</strong> NAP inconsistency (name, address, phone number differing between GBP and your website), choosing a category too broad or too specific, not verifying the listing, and leaving the profile without recent activity for months.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section id="section-3">
    <h2>3. Local SEO — ranking in organic search</h2>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-header">
        <span class="mc-num">02</span>
        <span class="mc-title">Local Search Engine Optimisation</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mc-body">
        <div class="mc-stats">
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Cost</span><span class="val">Low–Medium</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Setup Time</span><span class="val">Ongoing</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">First Leads</span><span class="val">3–6 months</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Compounds</span><span class="val">Yes — strongly</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Local SEO is the practice of optimising your website and online presence so that Google shows your business in search results when people search for your service in your area. It works alongside your GBP — the GBP controls your map pack appearance, while local SEO determines your position in the organic (non-map) search results below.</p>
        <p><strong>The three levers of local SEO:</strong></p>
        <ul class="action-list">
          <li><strong>On-page relevance:</strong> Your website must clearly signal what you do and where you do it. Each key service should have its own page. Location-specific pages (if you serve multiple areas) should name the specific town or suburb. Title tags, headings, and body copy should include natural variations of "[service] in [location]"</li>
          <li><strong>Citations:</strong> Consistent mentions of your business name, address, and phone number across directories — Yelp, TripAdvisor, local chamber of commerce, industry directories — signal legitimacy to Google. Inconsistent NAP across directories actively harms rankings</li>
          <li><strong>Links:</strong> Links from other locally-relevant websites (local news, community organisations, other local businesses) carry more local ranking weight than links from unrelated national sites</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Location pages for multi-area businesses:</strong> If you serve more than one city, suburb, or postcode, create a dedicated page for each service area rather than listing all locations on one page. Each page should have unique content specific to that area — local landmarks, service-specific information for that community, and locally-sourced testimonials where available. Duplicate location pages with only the city name changed are a common mistake that can trigger a Google quality penalty.</p>
        <p><strong>Timeline:</strong> Local SEO rarely produces meaningful results in under 90 days. Expect 3–6 months of consistent effort before seeing significant ranking improvements for competitive terms. Less competitive local markets can show results in 4–8 weeks.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section id="section-4">
    <h2>4. Facebook community marketing</h2>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-header">
        <span class="mc-num">03</span>
        <span class="mc-title">Facebook Local Groups &amp; Community Marketing</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mc-body">
        <div class="mc-stats">
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Cost</span><span class="val">Zero (organic)</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Setup Time</span><span class="val">Low</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">First Leads</span><span class="val">1–3 weeks</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Scales With</span><span class="val">Consistency</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Most towns, suburbs, and cities have active Facebook groups — local buy-sell-swap groups, neighbourhood community pages, local business directories, and interest-based groups for residents. These groups are populated by your exact target audience: people who live in your service area and regularly ask for recommendations, share experiences, and seek local services.</p>
        <p><strong>Organic community marketing (free):</strong> Join the relevant local groups. Participate genuinely — answer questions, provide useful local information, offer expertise without immediate sales intent. When people post asking for a recommendation for your type of service, a timely, helpful response is the most direct path to a local lead. A sustained presence over 4–8 weeks builds the kind of community visibility that generates organic recommendation requests without any direct promotion.</p>
        <p><strong>Facebook Local Ads (paid):</strong> Facebook's geographic targeting allows you to show ads exclusively to people within a specific radius of your business location — as precise as 1 kilometre. For service businesses with a clear offer (first appointment discount, free estimate, seasonal promotion), local Facebook ads can produce leads within 24–48 hours of launching a campaign. The barrier is creative — an ad with a strong visual and specific local relevance ("serving [suburb] since 2015") consistently outperforms generic national-style creative.</p>
        <p><strong>Facebook Lead Ads:</strong> A specific ad format that captures a prospect's contact information (name, phone, email) without requiring them to leave Facebook. The form pre-populates with their Facebook profile data, reducing friction significantly. For local service businesses where the next step is a phone call or appointment, Lead Ads reduce the barrier to expressing interest.</p>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Service businesses where trust and recommendation carry significant weight — home services, health and wellness, professional services, food and hospitality. Less effective for purely transactional retail where price comparison dominates the decision.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section id="section-5">
    <h2>5. Review generation and management</h2>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-header">
        <span class="mc-num">04</span>
        <span class="mc-title">Review Generation &amp; Management</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mc-body">
        <div class="mc-stats">
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Cost</span><span class="val">Zero–Low</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Setup Time</span><span class="val">1–2 hours</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">First Results</span><span class="val">1–4 weeks</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Compounds</span><span class="val">Yes — long-term</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Online reviews serve two lead generation functions simultaneously: they influence consumer decisions at the moment of evaluation (a potential lead choosing between you and a competitor), and they signal trust and relevance to Google's local ranking algorithm. A business with 200 Google reviews averaging 4.7 stars will consistently outperform a competitor with 20 reviews averaging 4.9 stars — volume matters alongside rating.</p>
        <p><strong>The review request system:</strong> Most satisfied customers do not leave reviews because they are never asked. The most effective review generation method is a simple, immediate request sent immediately after a positive interaction — before the customer's attention moves elsewhere. The timing window is 2–24 hours after a completed service or purchase.</p>
        <ul class="action-list">
          <li>Create a direct link to your Google Business Profile review form — go to your GBP, click "Get more reviews," and copy the short URL</li>
          <li>Send an SMS to every completed customer within 2 hours: "Thanks for choosing [business name], [customer first name]. If you were happy with the service, we'd really appreciate a quick Google review — it helps us enormously: [link]"</li>
          <li>Add the same link to your email receipts, invoices, and post-service follow-up emails</li>
          <li>Train every team member to verbally mention reviews at the point of service completion</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Negative review response:</strong> Every negative review should receive a professional, non-defensive response within 24 hours. Responding well to criticism is visible to prospective customers and often neutralises the damage of a single bad review. A business that responds thoughtfully to criticism signals accountability — which increases trust in those reading the reviews.</p>
        <p><strong>Platform priority:</strong> Google reviews are the highest priority because they directly affect local search rankings. Yelp, TripAdvisor, and industry-specific platforms matter depending on your business category — restaurants should prioritise all three; a specialist B2B service might focus exclusively on Google.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
