  <section id="section-6">
    <h2>6. Email and SMS follow-up marketing</h2>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-header">
        <span class="mc-num">05</span>
        <span class="mc-title">Email &amp; SMS Follow-Up Marketing</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mc-body">
        <div class="mc-stats">
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Cost</span><span class="val">Low</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Setup Time</span><span class="val">Medium</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">First Results</span><span class="val">Immediate</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Best For</span><span class="val">Repeat business</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>For local businesses, email and SMS marketing primarily serve two functions: converting past customers into repeat customers (the highest-ROI lead type for any local business) and reactivating lapsed customers who have not returned in a defined period. Both functions require only one thing: a customer contact list — which every business with a payment system already has, in some form.</p>
        <p><strong>Building the list:</strong> Collect email and phone number at every customer touchpoint — at purchase, during booking, via wifi login, through a loyalty programme sign-up, or in exchange for a first-purchase discount. The list is the asset. Every customer who gives you their contact details is a potential lead for every future promotion.</p>
        <p><strong>Email sequences for local businesses:</strong></p>
        <ul class="action-list">
          <li><strong>Welcome sequence:</strong> 3-email series sent after first purchase — confirmation of their decision, useful information about your service, and a second-visit incentive at email 3</li>
          <li><strong>Seasonal promotions:</strong> Timely offers relevant to your business calendar — the most underused high-ROI marketing activity for most local businesses</li>
          <li><strong>Win-back sequence:</strong> Triggered automatically when a customer has not returned in 90 days — a brief personal-feeling message with a reason to come back</li>
          <li><strong>Appointment reminders and follow-up:</strong> Automated reminders 24 hours before appointments reduce no-shows; follow-up surveys 24 hours after service generate reviews and identify service issues before they become public complaints</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>SMS vs. email:</strong> SMS open rates are dramatically higher (typically 90%+ within minutes vs. 20–40% for email over 24 hours), but SMS requires explicit opt-in and is subject to stricter regulations in most jurisdictions. Use SMS for time-sensitive messages — appointment reminders, same-day promotions, review requests. Use email for longer content, sequences, and less time-sensitive communications.</p>
        <p><strong>Platforms for local businesses:</strong> Mailchimp and MailerLite handle both email and basic SMS. Dedicated platforms like Birdeye, Podium, and Klaviyo offer more integrated local business tools combining reviews, SMS, and email in one system.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section id="section-7">
    <h2>7. Structured referral programmes</h2>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-header">
        <span class="mc-num">06</span>
        <span class="mc-title">Structured Referral Programmes</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mc-body">
        <div class="mc-stats">
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Cost</span><span class="val">Reward only</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Setup Time</span><span class="val">Low</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">First Leads</span><span class="val">Weeks</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Lead Quality</span><span class="val">Highest</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Referred customers are the highest-quality local leads available. They arrive pre-qualified (someone they trust has already endorsed you), convert at higher rates, spend more on average, and are more likely to refer further. A systematic referral programme turns your satisfied customer base into an ongoing lead source — without advertising spend.</p>
        <p><strong>Why most referral programmes fail:</strong> They are passive. Putting "tell a friend" on a receipt or website produces almost nothing. Effective referral programmes are active — they ask specifically, at a specific moment, with a specific incentive and a specific mechanism for the referral to happen.</p>
        <p><strong>The four elements of a working referral programme:</strong></p>
        <ul class="action-list">
          <li><strong>The ask:</strong> Direct and personal. "Mrs Johnson, we really value your business. Do you know anyone who might benefit from [service]? We would love to help them as well." — at the moment of a completed, positive interaction</li>
          <li><strong>The incentive:</strong> A meaningful reward for both the referrer and the referred customer. The most effective mechanics are dual-sided — the referrer gets a discount or gift; the new customer also gets a first-visit benefit. This gives the referrer something concrete to offer when making the recommendation</li>
          <li><strong>The mechanism:</strong> A simple way to make the referral — a unique referral code, a shareable link, or a physical referral card. Frictionless referral mechanics produce more referrals than complex ones</li>
          <li><strong>The follow-through:</strong> Track referrals, deliver rewards promptly, and thank the referrer personally when their referral converts. A thanked referrer refers again</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Digital referral tools:</strong> Platforms like ReferralHero, Referral Rock, and Yotpo Referral automate referral tracking and reward delivery. For small local businesses, a simple spreadsheet and a system for honouring rewards is sufficient to start — complexity can be added once the programme is producing results.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section id="section-8">
    <h2>8. Local business partnerships and joint ventures</h2>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-header">
        <span class="mc-num">07</span>
        <span class="mc-title">Local Business Partnerships</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mc-body">
        <div class="mc-stats">
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Cost</span><span class="val">Zero</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Setup Time</span><span class="val">Low–Medium</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">First Leads</span><span class="val">Weeks</span></div>
          <div class="mc-stat"><span class="label">Lead Quality</span><span class="val">Very High</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>A partnership with a complementary local business gives you direct access to their customer base — a warm local audience that has already demonstrated willingness to spend on services in your broader category. The leads arrive with a trusted recommendation, convert at high rates, and cost nothing beyond the reciprocal arrangement.</p>
        <p><strong>Complementary business examples:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Physiotherapist + personal trainer + sports nutrition retailer</li>
          <li>Real estate agent + mortgage broker + conveyancer + removalist</li>
          <li>Florist + wedding photographer + event venue + catering company</li>
          <li>Electrician + plumber + painter + property manager</li>
          <li>Accountant + financial planner + business lawyer</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>What a local partnership looks like in practice:</strong> A simple cross-referral arrangement — each party agrees to recommend the other when a customer's need falls into the partner's service area. This can be as simple as a verbal agreement reinforced by trading referral cards; it does not require formal contracts or complex infrastructure to produce results.</p>
        <p><strong>The stronger version — a lead-sharing network:</strong> Three to five complementary local businesses creating a shared customer communication channel — a monthly email covering all their offers, a joint social media presence, or a shared local events calendar. Each business contributes their customer list; all benefit from the combined audience. The combined reach of five small local business lists often exceeds 2,000–5,000 local email addresses — more effective reach than any single business's paid ad campaign at the same budget.</p>
        <p><strong>Local business associations:</strong> Chamber of commerce memberships and local business network groups (BNI chapters, local trade associations) create structured referral environments. The investment is a membership fee and attendance at regular meetings; the return is systematic introductions to complementary businesses and a referral culture that generates ongoing leads.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
